The radiograph shows a widened pubic symphysis and loss of cortical bone in the left femoral head, which indicates osteitis pubis and avascular necrosis of the femoral head respectively. Both of these conditions can be caused by Paget's disease, which is associated with elevated serum alkaline phosphatase levels. Elevated serum parathyroid hormone would suggest hyperparathyroidism and decreased serum calcium levels, but those are not associated with the patient’s symptoms. Decreased serum alkaline phosphatase would suggest hypophosphatasia, which is not associated with the patient’s symptoms.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The radiograph shows acetabular protrusio, which is commonly seen in Paget’s disease. Elevated serum alkaline phosphatase is a hallmark of Paget’s disease. Elevated serum parathyroid hormone is seen in hyperparathyroidism, and decreased serum calcium is seen in hypocalcemia, which are not the likely causes of the patient’s symptoms. Decreased serum alkaline phosphatase is seen in hypophosphatasia, which is a rare genetic disorder and is unlikely to be the cause of the patient’s symptoms.
